---
// A public recipe explainer set in /swiss: what makes a canelé custardy vs cakey,
// from real ratio analysis. Content only — the system lives in Explainer.astro.
import Explainer from '../../layouts/Explainer.astro';

const quiz = [
  { q: "You want a more custardy, softer interior. Which lever moves it most?",
    opts:["Add more sugar for moisture.","Lower the flour percentage toward 9–12%.","Use more whole eggs instead of yolks."], a:1 },
  { q: "A recipe is custardy but tastes hollow and flat. What's most likely low?",
    opts:["Fat — butter, cream, or yolks.","Sugar.","Total liquid."], a:0 },
  { q: "You push flour above 15% of batter. What happens to the interior?",
    opts:["It gets richer and darker.","It turns firm, cakey, bread-like.","It collapses and stays raw."], a:1 },
  { q: "Why lean on egg yolks rather than whole eggs?",
    opts:["Yolks make it sturdier and easier to unmold.","Yolks add fat and emulsification for a silky, rich set.","Whites would make it sweeter."], a:1 },
];
---
<Explainer
  title="What makes a canelé custardy — Andrew Shiau"
  description="An interactive explainer: the one ratio that decides whether a canelé is custardy or cakey."
  kicker="A recipe explainer · from six recipes, normalized"
  heading="What makes a canelé custardy."
  backHref="/work/explain/"
  backLabel="← Explain"
  quiz={quiz}
>
  <div class="grid"><p class="dek" style="grid-column:1/9">
    I normalized six popular canelé recipes to percentages of total batter weight
    to find what decides the interior. One number does most of the work.
  </p></div>

  <div class="grid"><div class="idea">
    <p class="k">The one idea</p>
    <p>Flour, as a percent of batter, is the lever between custardy and cakey. Everything else is richness and color.</p>
  </div></div>

  <div class="grid"><div class="rule"></div></div>
  <div class="grid"><div class="c1-2"><span class="sn">1</span></div><div class="c3-12"><h2>The number</h2></div></div>
  <div class="grid"><div class="num">
    <span class="big">9–14%</span>
    <span class="lab">flour, as a share of total batter, for a custardy interior <span class="g">— above ~15% it turns cakey and bread-like</span></span>
  </div></div>
  <div class="grid"><div class="scale">
    <div class="track">
      <div class="seg custard">← more custardy · soft, fragile</div>
      <div class="seg sweet">15%</div>
      <div class="seg cakey">cakey · firm, bread-like →</div>
    </div>
    <div class="ends"><span>flour 9%</span><span>flour 18%</span></div>
  </div></div>
  <div class="grid"><div class="body">
    <p>
      Across the six recipes, the ones people call "custardy" sit at 9–14% flour.
      Push past 15% and the crumb sets up firm. The recipe I use lands at the high
      end and leans on fat to stay rich rather than dry.
    </p>
  </div></div>

  <div class="grid"><div class="rule"></div></div>
  <div class="grid"><div class="c1-2"><span class="sn">2</span></div><div class="c3-12"><h2>What each part does</h2></div></div>
  <div class="grid"><div class="facts">
    <div class="frow"><div class="fm">Flour</div><div class="ftx">Structure. <b>More</b> = cakey and firm; <b>less</b> = custardy but fragile. The main lever.</div></div>
    <div class="frow"><div class="fm">Sugar</div><div class="ftx">Sweetness and caramelization. More = a darker shell; less = paler, less caramel.</div></div>
    <div class="frow"><div class="fm">Fat</div><div class="ftx">Butter, cream, yolk fat → richness. The lean recipes taste custardy but hollow. Fat is flavor.</div></div>
    <div class="frow"><div class="fm">Egg</div><div class="ftx">Yolks bind and emulsify for a rich set; more whole egg makes it sturdier but less silky.</div></div>
  </div></div>

  <div class="grid"><div class="rule"></div></div>
  <div class="grid"><div class="c1-2"><span class="sn">3</span></div><div class="c3-12"><h2>Check yourself</h2></div></div>
  <div class="grid"><div class="quiz" id="quiz"></div></div>

  <Fragment slot="foot">
    Source: my own ratio analysis of six canelé recipes —
    <a href="https://halfcadence.github.io/recipes/a/canele-ratio-analysis" target="offsite" rel="noopener" style="text-transform:none;letter-spacing:0;font-size:13px">halfcadence.github.io/recipes</a>.
  </Fragment>
</Explainer>

<style is:global>
  /* the flour-scale diagram — a labeled bar, custardy → cakey (canelé-only) */
  .scale{grid-column:3 / 11;margin:var(--unit) 0}
  .scale .track{display:flex;border:1px solid var(--ink);height:56px}
  .scale .seg{display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:12px;font-weight:700;
    letter-spacing:.06em;text-transform:uppercase;text-align:center;padding:0 6px}
  .scale .custard{flex:0 0 46%;color:var(--dim)}
  .scale .sweet{flex:0 0 8%;background:var(--accent);color:var(--on-accent);border-left:1px solid var(--ink);border-right:1px solid var(--ink)}
  .scale .cakey{flex:1;color:var(--dim)}
  .scale .ends{display:flex;justify-content:space-between;margin-top:8px;font-size:12px;color:var(--faint);font-weight:700;letter-spacing:.06em;text-transform:uppercase}
  @media(max-width:720px){ .scale{grid-column:1 / 13} }
</style>
